{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | image = Like a Virgin How Science Is Redesigning the Rules of Sex.jpg | image_size = | caption = | alt = | author = Aarathi Prasad | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = Virgin birth | genre = | publisher = [[Oneworld Publications]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = {{Start date|2012|09|01|df=y}} | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 272 | awards = | isbn = 9781851689118 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | preceded_by_quotation_marks = | followed_by = | followed_by_quotation_marks = | wikisource = }}
'''''Like a Virgin: How Science Is Redesigning the Rules of Sex''''' is a book by the former cancer genetics researcher Aarathi Prasad exploring [[Parthenogenesis|virgin birth]] through the [[whiptail lizard]], the [[stingless wasp]], the [[electric ant]] and the [[Beltsville Small White|Beltsville small white turkey]]. Prasad also explores the possibilities of virgin birth in humans and touches on [[teratoma|ovarian teratomas]].<ref>James McConnachie. [http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/culture/books/non_fiction/article1098754.ece "Like a Virgin: How Science Is Redesigning the Rules of Sex by Aarathi Prasad"], ''[[The Sunday Times]]'', 12 August 2012. Retrieved 26 May 2013.{{subscription required}}</ref>
The book also takes a historical look of sexless reproduction and ancient stories of virgin birth.<ref>Kira Cochrane. [https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/aug/17/sex-reproduction-aarathi-prasad "Why sex could be history"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 17 August 2012. Retrieved 19 January 2015.</ref>
