{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Lois Roberts | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Lois Martha Roberts | birth_date = c.1960<!-- {{birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}}. --> | birth_place = | death_date = c. July 1998<!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = [[Australia]]n | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }} '''Lois Martha Roberts''' (c. 1960 – c. July 1998) was an [[Australia]]n murder victim, whose death in 1998 remains unsolved.
==Background== Roberts was the daughter of Pastor Frank Roberts, a minister with the [[Church of Christ]] and an Aboriginal activist, and Muriel Roberts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thehoopla.com.au/i-remain-silent/|title=I will never be silent again|date=2011-10-30|access-date=2017-09-17|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111030005402/http://thehoopla.com.au/i-remain-silent/|archivedate=30 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She was the twin sister of the arts administrator and broadcaster [[Rhoda Roberts]], and the sister of Philip and Mark.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} Brought up and educated in the [[Lismore, New South Wales|Lismore]] region in northern New South Wales, Roberts trained as a hairdresser until, at age 20, she was seriously injured in a car accident sustaining permanent brain damage.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} She was rehabilitated sufficiently to care for herself and went to live on her own near Lismore.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} Subsequently, she had two children who were raised by her mother and twin sister.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}
==Disappearance== Roberts was last seen outside Nimbin Police Station on 31 July 1998.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northernstar.com.au/news/apn-her-killer-is-still-out/14069/|title=HER KILLER IS STILL OUT THERE|work=Northern Star|access-date=2017-09-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.9news.com.au/9stories/2016/10/31/09/21/a-sisters-heartbreak-over-the-unsolved-murder-of-her-twin|title=A sister's heartbreak over the unsolved murder of her twin|website=www.9news.com.au|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref> It would appear that she was abducted whilst hitch-hiking between [[Nimbin, New South Wales|Nimbin]] and Lismore and then tortured and abused before being killed. Her badly mutilated body was found about six months after her disappearance in January 1999. A [[bushwalker]] found the remains in Whian Whian State Forest, near [[Dunoon, New South Wales|Dunoon]], deep in thick bush some way off a fire trail.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/zoom/archive/rnews990112_0462_3994|title=Zoom|website=www.canberratimes.com.au|language=en-au|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref>
==Investigation and aftermath== The perpetrator or perpetrators of the crime have never been identified. An inquest was held in June 2002. The senior stipendiary magistrate of the Lismore Court Circuit, Jeff Linden, sitting as a [[Coroner's Court of New South Wales|coroner]] returned an open finding after a two-week hearing.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}
